00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.999
We have a long history of building Digital collections.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:54.999
It began in 1987 when Dr. Billington was appointed to the Library of Congress.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.999
He went on a tour of the country of town hall meetings in

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:11.999
10 locations throughout the country. He asked,

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:15.999
what do you want from the Library of Congress?

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.999
He met with teachers and librarians and faculty in universities

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.999
and pretty much the answer was uniformly the same.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:35.999
We want your content and we want to where we are,

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.999
not where you are. He took that to heart

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.999
and he came back to the Library of Congress with the

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:54.999
notion of what we must do is make our content more widely accessible.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.999
The Internet hadn't been invented by anyone yet so we

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:06.999
looked to CD-ROM technology to get content out

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.999
and we began digitizing collections in the very early 1990s.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:21.999
We focused on materials that would be focused on the K-12

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.999
community because that's where we thought the greatest

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:30.999
need was. We were sending CD-ROMs to schools

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:34.999
and libraries. We had 44 pilot institutions

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.999
and we went back to all of them to find out how they were

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.999
using the content so we could understand what else we should try to digitize.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:58.999
What was amazing to everyone involved is when we thought

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.999
this would be most useful to high school students,

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:10.999
in fact, all the way down to third grade,

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:15.999
students were making innovative uses of this digital

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:21.999
content and we saw even with this CD-ROM method,

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.999
students were beginning to ask important questions about

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.999
their history and about the world.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:34.999
We committed to making more and more of our primary source materials available to

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:41.999
schools and libraries around the country.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:47.999
In 1995, talked with the Library of Congress about this

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.999
digitization effort and said if you will raise private money,

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:59.999
we will put up some money.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.999
There was a three to one match with a three-part private

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:17.999
and one part Congress but that allowed us to expand our digitization efforts.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:27.999
We realized we had special collections that were held

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.999
nowhere else in the country. We had manuscripts and music and maps and film

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:40.999
and all kinds of things so we began to focus on

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:44.999
digitizing those special collections of materials rather than books.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.999
We were visited by Google when Google began to digitize collections.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.999
We decided our focus would be on special formats

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:05.999
and we did a little bit of experimenting but in the end,

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:10.999
we stayed with our primary focus. More recently,

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.999
we have begun to think far more broadly about what from

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.999
our collections should be readily accessible to the American people.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.999
We were pleased with the Sloan foundation agreed to fund

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:32.999
a digitization project that would allow us to identify

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:36.999
public domain books and our general collections

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.999
and make those available through a website as well.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:44.999
